### Appellate courts

<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Supreme_Court_of_Victoria,_Melbourne_(2011)_-_02.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Supreme_Court_of_Victoria,_Melbourne_(2011)_-_02.jpg/220px-Supreme_Court_of_Victoria,_Melbourne_(2011)_-_02.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Supreme_Court_of_Victoria,_Melbourne_(2011)_-_02.jpg/330px-Supreme_Court_of_Victoria,_Melbourne_(2011)_-_02.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Supreme_Court_of_Victoria,_Melbourne_(2011)_-_02.jpg/440px-Supreme_Court_of_Victoria,_Melbourne_(2011)_-_02.jpg 2x" data-file-width="640" data-file-height="480"></a><div class="thumbcaption"><div class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Supreme_Court_of_Victoria,_Melbourne_(2011)_-_02.jpg" class="mw-file-description"></a></div>The Victorian [Court of Appeal](/Supreme_Court_of_Victoria)</div></div></div>

Main article: [Appellate court](/Appellate_court)

When they finally get around to considering cases on appeal, [appellate courts](/Appellate_courts) generally have three primary courses of action: they can affirm the decision of a lower court, confirming its correctness; they can reverse it, deeming it incorrect; or they can [vacate](/Vacated_judgment) it, essentially nullifying the lower court's decision and often sending it back for further proceedings. It’s a delicate dance of judicial oversight, ensuring a semblance of consistency and rectitude within the broader legal framework.

It's worth noting that some courts maintain a curious dual function, acting both as reviewers of appeals and as forums for matters of "first instance," meaning they hear cases that originate directly within their jurisdiction. The [Supreme Court of the United States](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States) is a prime example, primarily serving as the nation's highest [appellate court](/Appellate_court) but retaining original jurisdiction over a highly limited range of cases, such as disputes between states or those involving foreign diplomats. This dual role can be seen as a practical necessity, or perhaps, an unwillingness to fully commit to a singular purpose.

Furthermore, many [jurisdictions](/Jurisdictions) employ a multi-tiered system of [appellate courts](/Appellate_courts). This often involves intermediate [appellate courts](/Appellate_courts) that handle the bulk of appeals, whose decisions are then themselves subject to review by even higher [appellate courts](/Appellate_courts). At the very pinnacle of this hierarchy in any given jurisdiction sits what is sometimes reverently referred to as a "court of last resort" or a "supreme court." The name implies an ultimate authority, a final arbiter beyond which there is no further legal recourse. A comforting thought, perhaps, for those who seek closure, but one that often belies the ongoing debates and interpretations that continue to shape the law long after a specific case has been "finally" decided.

